segments.text: The training of the OTCC in Chalcobesco in the rifle was giving orders to go up to this famous camp up in Illinois and participate in the National Rifle Field.
I won, and the Bullets had the hardest cut, and the next day they were sending because we had agreed to let the British Commando Force be coming to train there.
That was an outstanding disappointment.
I think I can understand that.
That was an outstanding disappointment.
I never did like the British Commando Forces.
I think they...
Let's see.
They performed outstandingly.
Let's go back to final review.
Your parents came?
Yes.
Any other special people?
No.
And then describe commencement.
Was commencement held in Guyon?
Guyon.
Do you remember who the speaker was?
Every name was called.
Every hand shaken.
Let's see.
Was Reveille around then?
We had the original Reveille.
Describe the original Reveille.
Did Reveille predate your arrival?
Was Reveille on the campus when you arrived as a freshman?
Who took care of Reveille then?
He literally did?
Yeah.
J. Harold Dunn?
Yeah.
Was he a student?
Let's see.
Oh, how good.
How good.
Silver Taps, where was that held?
Describe it.
Did the ceremony change as far as you know through the years?
Almost had Silver Taps for each individual.
I don't remember what year it was.
Most of the time you knew.
All right.
Student diversity.
Were there any Hispanic students?
Did you all identify them in any way different from the others?
Did they have, they didn't, were there some Mexican Americans?
Jewish, what about Jewish students?
Did you all have a special reference title for them?
Were there many international students?
Where were they from primarily?
All right.
We've got two more questions then.
As you're getting ready to leave with your degree, what kind of world did you think you
were entering?
What did you think was ahead of you?
All right.
After the Army, what did you think you were going to do?
I hoped to get a job.
Well, I had a job at that time.
Oh.
Did they give you any indication what your pay would be with Humble?
Did they come to the campus to do anything?
Now, what was your pay as a second lieutenant?
And you had a three-year obligation or two?
You had a contract?
About how many remained in the Corps their junior and senior year?
Did everybody?
Didn't you all have a different attrition each year?
Even if it didn't focus off on the junior?
All right.
Then the important question.
What did it mean to you, your life, that you went to Texas A&M?
It was a pretty realistic situation.
Why did you develop this deep love and gratitude for A&M?
A&M was a place where you could go and dress.
A&M gave me an opportunity to do different things.
I had an opportunity to develop one of the talents I had when I was a school teacher.
And, you know, you get older and you recommend it to other people.
And you see kids that have followed and made a good reaction.
Somehow or another, even now,
their kids go to A&M and seem to get a better direction in their life.
And students I see going to seminary,
and I'm not alone in sharing the fact that A&M has been a very important part of my life,
and the fellowship and the willingness to help this very big fraternity.
And there are a few people that are really taking to it today.
Let's see, that's the important one.
One I forgot.
Do you know anything about,
the TTs and any other supposed secret fraternities
when you were there?
What was the most prestigious appointment or a selection or election
that an undergraduate could have?
Did you by chance know Woody Varner?
He's a class ahead of you.
Derwood T. Varner from Cottonwood, Texas.
Let's quit there.
